\begin_layout Section

\size large
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Status is a complex sociological phenomenon.
 Often viewed as a static trait that depends on family or identity, one
 can assume that it is fixed over any reasonable time period for an econometric
 study.
 The rapid changes in wealth in all industrialized countries however have
 made such traditional notions of status rather obsolete.
 In the most recent research in health, sociology and economics, status
 is measured or proxied with characteristics that change over time such
 as occupation, education and income(see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NCVHS,PsakiSeidman2013,DiemerMistry2013"

\end_inset

 for a review).
 Family relationships or the social class are no longer adequate - statistically
 speaking - to explain the notion of socio-economic status.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Studies in health and welfare have built wealth indices to model SES.
 Of particular interest is the use of asset indices that track assets owned
 during the lifetime to measure SES (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013,McKenzie2005"

\end_inset

).
 Our goal in the current study is not to comment on the methodologies used
 in measuring SES but to understand how the assets and characteristics that
 determine the socio-economic status can influence non-durable consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our definition of status does not deviate much from the surveyed literature.
 Defined in terms of education, occupation, income and assets, SES is sensitive
 to rise in incomes and in asset ownership.
 If the accumulation of assets is rapid, it is likely to influence the non-durab
le consumption in the short run for a population of consumers.
 We believe that an intertemporal life-cycle model should continue to link
 the two bodies of literature i) on socio-economic status measurement and
 ii) on conspicuous consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to do so, we feel the need to discount Veblen's notion of the futility
 of conspicuous consumption on grounds of measurability of consumption -
 arguing that the items of conspicuous consumption can bring status utility
 primarily by indicating the high assets worth of the owners of the such
 items (endowments and/or identities) and thus they are not futile for the
 purposes of utility.
 One may consider them futile only in the sense that they don't have any
 value except through the high net asset worth of their owners.
 With the definition of status in terms of occupation, education, assets
 and identity, we measure the changes in asset ownership with respect to
 age, income, region, occupation, education only to answer how quickly the
 changes in indicators of SES can develop and possibly affect non-durable
 consumption.
\end_layout

