\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measurement of SES in the literature has relied on education, occupation,
 income and family relationships.
 The researchers have often proxied SES with a wealth based index based
 on these parameters (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NCVHS,PsakiSeidman2013,DiemerMistry2013"

\end_inset

).
 The usage of PCA and similar techniques is common in such studies.
 Quite a few researchers have used asset indices to study non-durable consumptio
n for measurement of inequality and welfare (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013,McKenzie2005"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The recording of assets ownership has been an important part of household
 surveys in both the developed and developing world.
 A few early studies on ownership of cars in the UK - for example - had
 used diffusion models to explain the proliferation of assets (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PyattDurable1964,DeatonEconConsumer"

\end_inset

).
 The introduction of electronic goods in the developing markets could also
 cause a similar proliferation of ownership and have an effect on the non-durabl
e consumption (through income and savings).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An econometric analysis of items that presumably improve the status of its
 buyer are prone to lead to a known tautological problem in demand analysis.
 If status-items are items that indicate the status of the buyer, then what
 conclusions are there to be derived from the observed high consumption
 on status items other than that the buyers of status items have high status?
 Such a paradox is quickly resolved by considering that the notions of status
 develop through expectation of change in future based on the wealth accumulated
 from past generations.
 This problem has been addressed by economists much before the introduction
 of game-theoretical approaches in microeconomics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Veblen's treatise
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset

 on conspicuous consumption is one such work which has inspired many studies
 - explaining most recently how the marginalised or minority communities
 spend differently on status items.
 However, as Veblen's ideas predate the times when household surveys were
 formalised in their post-war form, a lot of claims from Veblen (or on conspicuo
us consumption in the literature) are less obvious to verify.
 The concept of the futility of items of conspicuous consumption is not
 alone in this regard.
 Much later, commenting on the post-war developments in the Western society,
 Frederich Hirsch has argued that the human needs have expanded manifolds
 since the time when Adam Smith's invisible hand was known to work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits,GalbraithAffluent"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the rich pursuing their interests while poor gain social mobility
 is an exchange that no longer works in the modern society as it did in
 Europe of the eighteenth century.
 The changes in inequality in this case can be easily verified with the
 data and this view of industrial developments as a legacy of the race amongst
 the middle classes to achieve the higher social positions once held by
 the feudal elite - is one that is shared by many historians, economists
 and sociologists 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits,SchumpeterCapitalism"

\end_inset

.
 Still, there remains a lot in Hirsch's claims that is difficult to verify.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hirsch goes on to suggest that status differentials were necessary to create
 new markets - where positional goods and advertisement have a major role
 to play (see the model suggested for positional competition in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:HirschsModel"

\end_inset

).
 With the physical scarcity of goods (food and amenities) largely conquered,
 he argued that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scarcity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 becomes largely social in the developed countries.
 More commercialization (availability of previous unavailable items through
 money) leads to more scarcities and more competitions - hence instances
 of congestion (high demand with little chance of fulfilment) for a good
 develop - leading to increased status or positional competition in the
 society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key issue in developing an empirical understanding of the relationship
 between congestion and scarcity is of semantic nature.
 Scarcity seems a more general concept than mere unavailability or low supply
 of an item - as it seems to entail both unavailability of the item and
 the competition for it.
 Hirsch does differentiate between the physical scarcity (unavailability)
 and social scarcity (competition) but he also concludes that the boundary
 between physical and social scarcities can get blurred as the positional
 goods create a market for themselves.
 It is difficult to measure scarcity for a product or a range of products
 when the term encompasses both the physical scarcity (unavailability) and
 the perceived scarcity (what we feel as scarce).
 A consumer may indeed feel that the item is scarce because she cannot afford
 it or because the supply of the item is limited through some other mechanism
 (i.e.
 barriers exist in the distribution of the item) but while such felt scarcities
 appear relevant for consumption, we can only measure them relevant if they
 arise out of a relevant physical scarcity.
 Instead of attempting to define or measure felt scarcities themselves (as
 may be done in a subjective survey), we can expand the notion of the physical
 scarcity to include barriers created through status competitions, advertising
 or other social-psychological communication that create the sense of urgent
 demand for a status-carrying good.
 The fusion of physical and social scarcities however still does appear
 to be a tractable idea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another notion difficult to find an econometric equivalent of is the “scarcity
 through overuse” (which is emphasized as the engine of social scarcity
 in the modern Western society).
 Ambiguous as it may seem, it is even less relevant in the developing world
 where there simply aren't enough items to be consumed (likely a case of
 physical scarcity - using Hirsch's terminology) and all overuse could continue
 to be a luxury.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even so, Hirsch's ideas of scarcity and congestion are relevant in the developin
g countries (scarcity being interpreted as the lack of supply or unavailability
 of a particular commodity while congestion being the changes in income
 levels within social groups).
 The goal of status-related consumption in a developing economy - as much
 as anywhere else - is to allow a given population of individuals to associate
 themselves to those with perceived higher status (due to direct income
 or otherwise) in society.
 Despite the relevance of many of the ideas of Veblen and Hirsch, the measuremen
t and verification of the cultural trends identified by them are far from
 trivial due to the issues outlined above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Manski summarises such problems well with his remark that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the ambiguity of words permits a proliferation of concepts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Manski2000"

\end_inset

).
 It does appear that resolving ambiguities in terminology can make many
 social commentaries less compelling.
 Verbal reasoning - as Manski further elaborates - is less precise than
 mathematical argument
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Manski2000"

\end_inset

 even though it can be more evocative than the latter.
 One such example is Wilson's (1987) discussion of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

underclass
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Manski2000"

\end_inset

.
 In general, as Manski finds, when the economists have used the ideas of
 a social capital, they have made several limiting assumptions about the
 group composition before analysis.
 For example, a study by Boijas (1991) claims that persons interact with
 members of their own ethnic group.
 Other studies interpret social capital in their own way - allowing the
 idea of social capital to remain a rather vague concept.
 Hirsch's claims too - therefore - need not be scrutinised much except for
 the search of their econometric equivalence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To avoid the complexities of language and social observation, the behavioural
 sciences often design experiments where subjects can choose amongst well-define
d options.
 While it is difficult to scale up results from such smaller, often artificial,
 environments to higher levels of organisation in the society, such experiments
 remain an important tool to identify factors that have an impact on human
 motivations for consumption (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"

\end_inset

 for arguments both for and against this approach).
 While generalising results from such experiments in the wider population,
 there is the implicit assumption that the status competitions are inherent
 in all members of the population (so that a sample bias is ruled out).
 The arguments by Robert Frank seem pertinent to this assumption in that
 striving to achieve more than others may very well be ingrained in our
 hormones(see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"

\end_inset

).
 Frank enumerates many empirical examples to support his arguments.
 Exploring incomes amongst professors competing for grants - for example
 - Frank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"

\end_inset

 notes that neither the Permanent Income model nor the productivity model
 explains the distribution of income.
 What offers a better explanation is the presence of status competition
 among the professors.
 Similarly, he demonstrates that in the absence of monopolies, it becomes
 difficult for corporations to survive by rewarding talent alone and they
 are thus compelled to depend on status competitions for income distribution
