\begin_layout Standard
Another practical problem arises in the developing world because of the
 predominant use of recall method in expenditure survey.
 A relevant anomaly is the Deaton Paxson paradox(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonPaxsonParadox"

\end_inset

) - i.e.
 the observed decrease in food expenditure per head as household size rises
 (with constant total outlay per head).
 The likely cause for the paradox is presence of errors correlated with
 household size in the data that results in possible overestimation of the
 consumption of recalled items
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GibsonDeatonPaxson"

\end_inset

.
 Caution must therefore be taken (or a correction applied) when mixing expenditu
res from recall and diary methods (We note that the LSMS data on Tanzania
 records both diary and recall expenditures and we're careful not to stress
 on relative importance of one group vs the other while merging the respective
 expenditures).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
While the visibility elasticities may not be compared across geographic
 boundaries without above considerations, a comparison within the country
 can provide insights into the effect of certain demographic factors on
 visible consumption (as long as the criteria of visibility is clear).
 This has been the central theme for most of the studies on conspicuous
 consumption surveyed.
 More than to improve the measurement of visibility, the studies are interested
 in identifying the demographic parameters that explain the log-expenditure
 of visibility basket as is.
 The general regression equation for such a study is the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ln(vis_{i})=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}\cdot Dem_{i}+\beta_{2}\cdot ln(pInc_{i})+\epsilon\label{eq:lnvis_regression-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $vis_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the total visible consumption of the household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (accumulated over the chosen visibility basket), 
\begin_inset Formula $Dem_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of demographic indicators under consideration and 
\begin_inset Formula $pInc_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the permanent income - proxied by total expenditure.
 Households with higher total expenditure are far more likely to be those
 with higher visible expenditure.
 Thus, total expenditure (on the right side of the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lnvis_regression-1"

\end_inset

) makes it an endogenous variable for the dependent variable : 
\begin_inset Formula $ln(vis_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 A different approach is taken by Jaikumar et al (2015) who use weights
 in the basket rather than visible expenditure levels - so that visible
 expenditure is not subject to the endogeneity problem that arises due to
 total expenditure being on the right hand side and visible expenditure
 on left hand side of the equation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq"

\end_inset

 (The proportion of visible expenditure with respect to the total expenditure
 could be the same for those with higher total expenditure and lower total
 expenditure).
 However, since data on income is often poor or sparse in the developing
 countries, total expenditure turns out to be the most frequent choice for
 a proxy of permanent income (
\begin_inset Formula $pInc_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a key control parameter for the analysis of visible consumption).
 In most of the studies, the said endogeneity of total expenditure is resolved
 by a choice of appropriate instruments - e.g.
 income, cubic-income, positive-income dummies or occupation codes.
 These instruments identified by Charles et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CharlesHurstRace"

\end_inset

 are reported to be quite strong in the studies surveyed as part of this
 note (Sargan and Wu-Hausman tests confirm endogeneity and the effectiveness
 of chosen instruments).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A lot of studies have used the above framework to identify social factors
 that are relevant to difference in visible preferences.
 In India, these factors are religion and caste - while in South Africa
 and United States, race seems to have significance (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA,CharlesHurstRace,OmoriSmithVisRace"

\end_inset

).
 The developing countries may also offer a less consumerist and less individuali
stic agrarian environment where mundane and seemingly unvaried expenditures
 (lesser number of status items) are more visible than in a relatively more
 individualistic and industrialized society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
For visibility to bear significance in an environment of severe inequalities
 and scarcities, an association with higher income becomes relevant.
 Khamis et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

 therefore perform a slightly more detailed survey by asking what an individual
 whose consumption is noticed would do when her income rises (by 20%).
 This quantifies the expectation of how others infer the increases in total
 expenditure (income).
 The items where consumers expect the consumption to rise with increased
 income are those that associate with higher income and are declared 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conspicuous
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
In a developing economy, the criterion for status consumption is clearly
 not just noticeability any more.
 Visible consumption does detail the mechanics of status competitions in
 a narrower sense where consumers participate in a market to increase their
 perceived status - but it does not provide an adequate picture of status
 and consumption.
 One reason why other factors dominate is that markets are underdeveloped
 in the developing world and social status is largely yielded through severe-inc
ome differences and social strata.
 The second and probably more significant reason is that status signaling
 does not exist in a society as an inherent need for visible appeal amongst
 humans.
 Instead visible consumption matters because the item in consideration is
 associated with higher status (in the same sense that Veblen had talked
 about in his 19th century treatise
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice also that the focus on visible consumption alone benefits from a
 key assumption based on Veblen's arguments - which is that conspicuous
 consumption is essentially futile - therefore the visible/status utility
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
By assuming that a visible (or conspicuous) good serves no utility other
 than of status, we can be sure that the item in consideration does not
 have any utilitarian value and combine all the products in the visible
 category to talk about the status benefit that the consumer receives (see
 Corneo et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

can be separated from non-status utility - but this separability criterion
 verified in all of the literature around conspicuous consumption.
 An ardent follower of Veblen may indeed find watches and makeup products
 as a social waste and eventually 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

futile
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but it is difficult to argue that housing or shoes too would only offer
 status benefits.
 Our view is that consumers don't buy an item purely for status needs -
 more so in the developing countries.
 Instead of limiting ourselves to visible consumption as the particular
 mechanics of status signaling - where consumers buy items in a common market
 and (presumably) over-weigh on items that are more noticeable - we attempt
 to understand how reasons such as unavailability of items and disparities
 of services across regions could influence the needs of consumers with
 respect to the desire to achieve status through non-durable consumption
 and assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first econometric study that was undertaken with a panel data of savings
 and income was by Duesenberry (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duesenberry1949"

\end_inset

)- who had noticed disparate savings ratios amongst social groups in one
 of tshe first econometric studies on status-related consumption (before
 Milton Friedman addressed the same problem with the permanent income hypothesis
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FriedmanConsumption1957"

\end_inset

).
 Even though Veblen's (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset

) view of status involving items of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

futility
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 was not shared by Duesensberry either, we find that Veblen's view of status
 consumption as a combination (or balance) of two opposing tendencies could
 be useful for modeling purposes.
 These are the tendencies of a consumer i) to distinguish oneself from others
 and ii) to follow others
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Veblen has articulated these tendencies as that of invidious comparison
 and pecuniary emulation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 - that have been described by the snob and bandwagon effects in more recent
 literature (Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

).
 It is easy to obfuscate these two opposing tendencies by asserting that
 both the tendencies exist in individuals at the same time - a claim that
 would  make the measurement of status-consumption rather impossible.
 On the other hand, by attempting to measure the relative importance of
 the two tendencies that are reflected in habits and expenditure over the
 lifetime, it is possible to see to what extent the stock purchases and
 non-durable expenditure are influenced by socio-economic status.
 In more technical terms, we set ourselves to find how well a life-cycle
 model could explain the change in savings rates of individuals over the
 life-time and whether quality measurements of the purchases of the non-durable
 items would change with asset ownership over their lifetime.
\end_layout

