\begin_layout Section

\size large
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:ModelforStatus"

\end_inset

A model for measurement of status-related consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

 - one that considers a ranking function for every individual so that consumptio
n is seen as a way to transform the income ranking of a population i.e.
 individuals improve their perception in society through consumption to
 overcome their income rank in the society.
 It can be argued that anyone in less than the highest income group (more
 specifically -the highest quantile of the all status determinants minus
 that of consumption) would benefit from a short-term expense on status-related
 nondurable consumption.
 Therefore, if conspicuous consumption does exist in a society, one can
 claim that the rank of expenditure on nondurable items (or utility) and
 assets rank (or utility) must differ for the consumers in medium quantiles.
 The status ranking that is imparted to an individual can be seen as a combinati
on of a ranking of expenses on non-durable items and that of asset ownership.
 Unlike in the Ireland and Corneo models, we assume that all consumption
 items can potentially impart status.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The clarification in terminology is due here - particularly since we have
 stated that we don't consider conspicuous consumption as futile.
 A status item for us in an item that can change the status of an individual
 by increasing the 
\shape italic
\size small
likelihood
\shape default
\size default
 of improving status over the long-run - which continues to be determined
 by education, occupation, assets and family interactions.
 Non-durable consumption in this model could be either completely futile
 from a status point of view or it must have a direct influence on status.
 In the model we intend to set up, the non-durable consumption is only futile
 in long-run since it doesn't improve long-run ownership of assets or change
 in social interactions.
 We believe that the utility of conspicuous consumption lies only in increasing
 the likelihood of social interactions with those with better status- letting
 the model parameters change of asset growth be a function of non-durable
 consumption.
 Therefore, we don't completely reject Veblen's idea of futility of conspicuous
 consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The empirical problems of finding a clear boundary between conspicuous and
 non-conspicuous items are thus also circumvented by relying on expensive
 nondurable consumption and long-term ownership as the key determinants
 of status.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also intend to indicate that the snob and bandwagon items can also be
 understood in terms of the asset-based model.
 A consumer chooses a snob item to protect her position in the societal
 ranking and a bandwagon item to promote herself in the ranking.
 Both non-durable items and assets can therefore be of snob or bandwagon
 type.
 It is the consumer's relative positioning in the social ranking that determines
 whether a new item she purchases is snob or bandwagon type.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are hence two levels of substitiution in the mdoel.
 First is the substitution between assets and non-durable consumption.
 The further substitution at the finer level exists between within categories
 of non-durable consumption - each of which offer an expensive variety for
 consumption.
 As an example, the former substitution could be between saving for furniture
 and overspending on clothes while the latter could be between consuming
 cheaper grains and consuming exotic meat.
 The conditions on seaparability of utility function between i) expensive
 non-durable consumption and ii) asset purchases is likely to be quite stringent.
 Further, the combining of diary data with recall data could make any conclusion
s of the combined model for the two substitutions too error-prone.
 (see the Deaton-Paxston paradox in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:LiteratureReview"

\end_inset

).
 Hence, we visit the two substitutions independently in the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Accumulation of Assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The accumulation of assets over a life-time can be modeled as an intertemporal
 life-cycle model.
 We formulate a discrete model first and walk through its details before
 adding continuity to the model parameters in order to to add differentiability
 to the marginal utility function and the constraints of a demand function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the discrete model, let's consider a consumer who gets a salary of 
\begin_inset Formula $I(t)$
\end_inset

 over the year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 if the salary of our consumer 1000$ per month, then 
\begin_inset Formula $I(1)=12000$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I(0)=0$
\end_inset

).
 Assume that starting at her working age, she does not have any assets (an
 assume that is to be relaxed in any empirical study) and that she expects
 her salary to grow at a linear rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 per year (so that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=.06$
\end_inset

 then in 40 years (
\begin_inset Formula $t=40$
\end_inset

 ) at her retirement, her income would be ~10,000 per month).
 We assume that she wants to give everything to charity at retirement and
 check herself into a health facility- which she would also have to pay
 for.
 Her wealth would be zero at retirement - i.e.
 no savings, no income nor even any assets - all of which would be sold
 off and paid out to a charity and the health facility (alternatively, she
 can pass it all on to her children).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that all individuals in the population are like our representative
 consumer - but with different starting salaries and habits even though
 they all have similar preferences (i.e.
 all else equal they all prefer health over a TV, a cell-phone over a radio
 etc.).
 We can assume that all assets are managed by a large firm (owing its success
 to preferences being the same for everybody) which provides furniture,
 housing and all amenities at a flat upfront cost.
 Even the health facility - which our consumers plan to show up at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=R(=40)$
\end_inset

 along with other assets (and policies) are managed by this asset company
 - where all assets purchased have a finite lifetime 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}$
\end_inset

.
 The depreciation of the assets is not necessarily linear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a first cut analysis, let's also assume that there is no credit or borrowing
 in the market (an assumption that is not so far fetched in a developing
 economy).
 The no-credit assumption implies that the consumer can only save to buy
 more of the only asset available in the market.
 Therefore, after 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

(=5) years of working starting in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 let's say, the consumer's salary would be 
\begin_inset Formula $I(t)(1+\alpha)^{\tau-1}$
\end_inset

(=1400$/month), so that the total income she has earned is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=0}^{\tau-1}I(j+1)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(=\sum_{i=0}^{4}12000\times(1.06)^{i}=67645.12)$
\end_inset

.
 Out of this wealth, she could have purchased assets from a portion of her
 income (let's say
\begin_inset Formula $50000\$$
\end_inset

) and decide that she does not want more assets for the rest of her life.
 Alternatively, her life circumstances might have changed and she may need
 a bigger house or a more expensive house - and hence she would need an
 assets upgrade more urgently.
 We assume that such events can happen at any point in her life - although
 they have a higher probability around 
\begin_inset Formula $t=10$
\end_inset

.
 Being a rational consumer with full information, the consumer is aware
 of the probability of the such events occurring at every year.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{K}(t)$
\end_inset

 denote the number of year until which the consumer would need to save in
 order to purchase asset the desired 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 at price 
\begin_inset Formula $P(K)$
\end_inset

 so that if she sets her eyes on an asset 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 then she would purchase the asset at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\delta_{K}(t)$
\end_inset

 - as long as there are no changes in her circumstances.
 It may happend that at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=30$
\end_inset

 or some time before 
\begin_inset Formula $t=40$
\end_inset

 when she retires, the consumer sheds some of her assets - so as to prepare
 for retirement.
 It would thus mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{K}=0\forall K$
\end_inset

 after this event at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=30$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simplify the supply side and depreciation concerns, let's assume further
 that the health services - that are managed by the asset company - have
 an upfront cost (
\begin_inset Formula $A_{H}$
\end_inset

 =500,000 USD) and a finite lifetime 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}$
\end_inset

 as do all the other assets 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 The consumer wishes to both live longer and have higher assets throughout
 her life.
 She knows that if she doesn't pay the upfront cost at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=30$
\end_inset

, her probability of living longer would be lower.
 So she wishes to set aside a fixed portion 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 of her income per year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 towards this investment.
 Since all assets are managed by the one asset company, every other asset
 and service is treated just the same by the consumer i.e.
 a constant saving rate is maintained until the accumulated savings match
 the desired asset cost level.
 It is important to remember that in this model, the probability of living
 longer and healthier is also an asset that would need to be purchased at
 a fixed price in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some others might want to start saving later than 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 or submit a higher proportion to their health as they grow older - but
 we can assume that they always all set aside a proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 of he salary - so that the minimum possible non-durable consumption is
 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 all income is saved (the maximum 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 is the monthly income itself).
 We can thus state that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
0 & \le\gamma(t)\le I(t)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

 At any point 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, the consumer's savings account can be represented by
\begin_inset Formula $c(t)$
\end_inset

 - which is intended to be spent towards an asset.
 If the assets owned by a consumer at year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(K)$
\end_inset

 denotes the price of the asset 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t)$
\end_inset

 is the sum of all savings minus the amount that was spent on assets i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
c(t) & =\sum_{\tau=0}^{t}\gamma(\tau)I(\tau)-\sum_{K\in\Lambda_{t}}P(K)=\psi(\Lambda_{t},P,\delta,\alpha,I)
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The business model of the asset company is based on selling packages with
 discrete cost value of assets - which are assumed to be in unlimited supply.
 The asset levels up for sale by the company can be sorted based on costs
 so that
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\mathscr{A}=}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\{A_{1},A_{2},...\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A_{1})<P(A_{2})<P(A_{3})<....$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 1K, 2K, 10K, 50K, 100K, 500K,....).
 The cost of the highest asset is limited only by the size of the economy,
 a consumer can buy the next asset unit as long as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
c(t+1) & \le\sum_{K\in\Lambda*_{t+1}\backslash\Lambda_{t}}P(K)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

Here, the desired future level of assets is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{t+1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that the only way for our consumer to save for an asset is with
 a fixed proportion every month.
 For some asset level that are far beyond her reach, she would have to save
  for more than one year (there is always an asset in the market that she
 cannot buy).
 At equilibrium, the consumer would set the portion 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 of annual income per year (notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t+1)=\gamma(t)+c(t)-\sum_{K\in\Lambda*_{t+1}\backslash\Lambda_{t}}P(K)$
\end_inset

) in a way that she can pay exactly for what she wants at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\tau_{K}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $1\le\tau_{K}\le R-t$
\end_inset

.
 The inequality therefore becomes an equality: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
c(t+\tau_{K}) & =\sum_{K\in\Lambda_{t+\tau_{K}}}P(K)\label{eq:savings_value}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

 Therefore, at the end of the year, the consumers can spend all of 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t+1)=\sum_{K\in\Lambda_{t+1}}P(K)$
\end_inset

 or the consumer may roll over the account value 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t+1)$
\end_inset

 over to the next year when she faces the same choice.
 The proportion
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{*}(t+1)$
\end_inset

 is adjusted so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{*}(t+1)I(t+1)$
\end_inset

 goes towards the desired asset.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t+1)=c(t)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t+1)=0$
\end_inset

 and it follows that no assets were planned for the future (since all future
 assets are planned with the proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

).
 This is because of our assumption that all planned assets are purchased
 through contributions 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 that add to 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t)$
\end_inset

.
 The rest of the salary i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $I(t)-\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 is always spent in the non-durable expenditure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rebalancing of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{K}(t)$
\end_inset

 every year is equivalent of stochastic component to the utility function
 whose expected value is maximised by the representative consumer.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{K}(t)$
\end_inset

 is simply the expected number of years that the consumer wants to save
 for until she achieves the next desired asset level.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 grows at the same rate as income 
\begin_inset Formula $I(t)$
\end_inset

 until 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{K}(t)$
\end_inset

 when it is used up from the accumulated 
\begin_inset Formula $c(t)$
\end_inset

 for the purchase of asset level 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 If the consumer intends to to purchase 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in the year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, then we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\sum_{j=t}^{t+\delta_{\kappa}}\gamma(j) & =c(t+\delta_{\kappa})-c(t)=P(\kappa)\label{eq:gamma_delta}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

If the consumer decides to reduce the savings 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{K}$
\end_inset

 gets increased accordingly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's illustrate the running of this discrete model with an example.
 If our consumer has 
\begin_inset Formula $50,000$
\end_inset

$ worth of assets and she wants an item of 
\begin_inset Formula $10,000\$$
\end_inset

 value, where here yearly salary is 
\begin_inset Formula $9,000$
\end_inset

 at year 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, then she must save 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[k,\delta+k-1]$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

 years so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=k}^{k+\delta_{\kappa}-1}\gamma(k)=\gamma(k)\sum_{j=0}^{\delta_{\kappa}-1}(1+\alpha)^{j}=c(k+\delta_{\kappa})-c(k)=10000$
\end_inset

 (see Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma_delta"

\end_inset

).
 If
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\kappa}(k)=3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=.06$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{*}(k)\sim3140$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{*}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the planned 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{*}(k)$
\end_inset

 so the consumer must save 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(k)$
\end_inset

 this year to be able to be on track to afford the item in 3 years.
 If she could not save this much in the year i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(k)<\gamma^{*}(k)=3140$
\end_inset

 (more than 
\begin_inset Formula $I(k)-\gamma(k)$
\end_inset

 is spent in non-durable items), then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\kappa}(k+1)$
\end_inset

 for the next year would no longer be 2, but a new value that satisfies
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=0}^{\delta_{\kappa}(t+1)}(1+\alpha)^{k}\gamma^{*}(k+1)=10000-\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{K}(t)$
\end_inset

 would thus depend on past fixings of
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{K}^{*}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming that the consumer still wants the asset at the same even after
 having missed the target for year 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 with
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(k)=2000$
\end_inset

, then as far as the accounting goes, she has 
\begin_inset Formula $50000\$$
\end_inset

 worth of assets, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=$
\end_inset

2000$ saved for the future purchase of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(k+1)=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{*}(k+1)=3880$
\end_inset

.
 If she can postpone the asset purchase until another year then
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(t+1)=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{*}(t+1)=2514$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that she does sell her owned assets to gain new because that would
 still keep her net worth the same - an opportunity that has already been
 considered by the asset company.
 If the consumer doesn't keep up with her plans, then it is even possible
 that she never acquires the asset she had set the target for
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The evolution of
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\kappa}$
\end_inset

 takes account of missed opportunities.
 There are some assets (e.g.
 the health facility) that can be acquired until a certain time failing
 which they can never be had.
 The order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

 therefore changes with time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
