\begin_layout Subsection
Expensive non-durable consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Price differentiation in the market matters for the way a consumer sets
 herself apart from others through selection of higher-priced items.
 The more the price differentiation exists within a functional category,
 higher is the likelihood for the consumers to indicate status through purchase
 of higher priced item.
 If markets of items are perfect and differences in status as well as prices
 exist in an economy, then it is certain that those with higher purchasing
 power would attempt to maintain their status with the purchase of higher
 priced items.
 All expensive items cannot carry status (e.g.
 medical equipment) but all items that carry status must be priced higher.
  
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We cannot base ourselves on the price-based model alone because of the lack
 of detailed price information in the LSMS survey - but we can use the observati
on whether expensive items were consumed by a consumer or not.
 Exotic meats or recreational electronic equipments are likely to be used
 by fewer and richer consumers in the survey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given our earlier discussion on scarcity, we must clarify that the scarcity
 of the item is not implied by how sparsely it is used by the consumers.
 For example, medical equipment or musical instruments would always be limited
 to a certain section of the population - but they become a status product
 
\shape italic
only
\shape default
 if there are low-price substitutes that exist for them.
 Therefore, an item's low distribution may count towards status only as
 long as it can be viewed as superior to other substitutes (through price
 if the markets exist for the category).
 Notice also that participation of consumers in the same market is key in
 the view of the status advantage through price differences.
 Certain items may have higher price varieties due to transport costs -
 so if the markets where consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 participate are affected by different supply-side issues then it would
 be erroneous to consider status differences on grounds of price differences
 observed by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 It makes sense in fact to think of the gain (loss) of status by being in
 a region where more items are available (unavailable).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, note that the asset based model is not concerned with the differences
 in visibility of items within a functional category, the measurement of
 visibility index (as employed by Heffetz
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "heffetz_visibility"

\end_inset

 and Khamis et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

) is not relevant to the model.
 In other words, we are not concerned with whether items within a functional
 group (e.g.
 food, personal products or housing) are more or less visible with respect
 to each other - hence the difference between values of a visibility index
 for shampoo and that for body-oil is rather irrelevant for the model.
 The idea of visibility is incorporated only in the preference for visibility
 that exists for functional categories (food,energy, housing etc.).
 While clothes could be deemed more visible than an investment policy -
 a more specific order of visibility within a category (e.g.
 shampoo vs body-oil) is unimportant.
\end_layout

